<paragraph blockId="15.[264,1324,1529,1755]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Twenty­seven species of 
<taxonomicName box="[574,738,1530,1555]" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Mesocordylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[574,738,1530,1555]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Mesocordylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known from 
<collectingCountry box="[959,1049,1529,1555]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Mexico</collectingCountry>
through to 
<collectingCountry box="[1199,1320,1529,1555]" name="Argentina" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. There are eleven species of 
<taxonomicName box="[588,752,1570,1595]" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Mesocordylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[588,752,1570,1595]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Mesocordylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[788,916,1569,1595]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[972,1069,1569,1595]" name="Panama" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Panama</collectingCountry>
. Of these eleven species, four are restricted to 
<collectingCountry box="[567,694,1609,1635]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[749,846,1609,1635]" name="Panama" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Panama</collectingCountry>
. One species is described herein as new.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[264,1324,1529,1755]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Adults of 
<taxonomicName box="[432,595,1650,1675]" class="Insecta" family="Dryophthoridae" genus="Mesocordylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[432,595,1650,1675]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Mesocordylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are most frequently collected at lights and in flight intercept traps. Occasionally, adults are found associated with fallen logs. The immature stages are unknown. Vaurie (1970, 1973) revised the genus.
</paragraph>
